[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Clarifying JUnit constructor rules**\n\nI'm thinking about constructor requirements in JUnit. It seems like JUnit 5 supports constructor injection but insists that test classes must not be abstract and should have a single constructor. Wait, I’m unsure if JUnit Jupiter allows multiple constructors. Actually, no, if a class has multiple constructors, it throws a PreconditionViolationException stating that a single constructor is required. I need to confirm if that’s the case!\n\n**Exploring reflection access**\n\nI’m wondering if `org.jdom.xpath.XPath` can instantiate a package-private class from a different package. The constructor is public, but the class itself isn’t, so that makes things tricky. I think accessing it would throw an `IllegalAccessException` since the caller isn't from the same package. But if I use `getConstructor`, would it matter if the constructor is public? I need to check if a package-private class with a public constructor can still return with `getConstructors`. My head is spinning a bit here!\n\n**Evaluating Java test structure**\n\nI need to keep tests in a dedicated Java file, ensuring a one-to-one mapping between report classes and generated test files. I'm wondering if adding a helper file would violate that guideline. Maybe I could name it something like XPathImplementation, but it can't be a test class. Making the implementation a public top-level class while keeping it in the same file seems impossible. I could think of using a single constructor with a String for JUnit, but that would likely cause issues with parameter resolution. This is getting complicated!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_074283bac3f16e0b0169ef88358b1881978c0a3682d1662c08\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp74hIb-mzI3viYED73mZcFvU-S8gEoIGCzd6fgv7yMlms6hMH0nElwjA2red39-_LDN1FscNsUQ9wJ07tchfbxVj1Jikflke6UQJj4lsCza1IJaEyCS_ecUrnS1_aBY